  "prompt": "Does the warranty on the car electrical wiring lapse in case one gets a music system fitted from outside and not from the company showroom?",
  "response": "Whether the warranty on a car\u2019s electrical wiring lapses due to an aftermarket installation, such as a music system fitted outside the company showroom, can vary based on several factors:\n\n1. **Warranty Terms**: Most manufacturers provide warranty terms that specify what is covered and what constitutes a warranty void. If the installation of the aftermarket system results in damage or issues with the electrical wiring or any other part of the car, it may void that part of the warranty.\n\n2. **Installation Quality**: If the aftermarket installation is done improperly and causes electrical or mechanical issues, the warranty could be impacted. Conversely, a professionally installed system that doesn\u2019t interfere with existing components should not typically void the warranty.\n\n3. **Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act (U.S.)**: In the United States, this law protects consumers from having their warranties voided solely because aftermarket parts are used, as long as the aftermarket parts do not cause damage. However, warranty coverage may still be affected if the installation leads to issues.\n\n4. **Documentation**: Always check the car's warranty documentation and speak with the dealership or manufacturer directly for the most accurate information regarding warranty implications of aftermarket installations.\n\nTo ensure coverage, it's a good idea to consult the warranty booklet and consider using professional installation services that are recognized by the manufacturer.",
